{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἐράω</b>,<br /> <br /><Level1><b>__A</b></Level1> used in <i>active</i> only in <i>present</i> and <i>imperfect</i> (which in Poetry are ἔραμαι, ἠράμην), <i>Ionic dialect</i> <b>ἐρέω</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 25.3 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]: <i>imperfect</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ἤρων 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.108, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “fragment” 161, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ach.” 146:\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —<i>passive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ἀντ-ερᾶται Xenophon Historicus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Symposium” 8.3 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; <i>optative</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ἐρῷο [prev\\. author] “Hier.” 11.11 \">Refs</a>]; <i>infinitive</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ἐρᾶσθαι Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus [{1-2nd c.AD}] “Brutus” 29 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>], etc.; <i>participle</i> ἐρώμενος (see. below):— also <b>ἐράομαι</b>, 3rd.<i>person</i> etc for 1st.<i>person</i>, 2nd.<i>person</i> <i>singular</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ἐρᾶται Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus [{1-2nd c.AD}] 2.753b, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Gym.” 48 (ἐράασθε see entry ἔραμαι): all other tenses will be found under ἔραμαι\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]:—<b>love,</b> with <i>genitive</i> <i>person</i>, properly of the sexual passion, <b>to be in love with</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"(οὐκ ἐρᾷ ἀδελφὸς ἀδελφῆς..οὐδὲ πατὴρ θυγατρός Xenophon Historicus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 5.1.10), ἤρα τῆς..γυναικός 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 9.108 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>], etc.: with <i>accusative</i> <i>cognate</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ἐρᾶν ἔρωτα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 32, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Smp.” 181b: _absolutely_, ἐρῶν\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>a lover,</b> variant in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 1.80 (_plural_), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “fragment” 149.8 (_plural_); opposed to ἡ ἐρωμένη _the beloved one,_ 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.31, 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “P.” 3.196; [ὁ] ἐρώμενος Xenophon Historicus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Symposium” 8.36, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phdr.” 239a, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Eq.” 737 (_plural_); τὸν ἐρώμενον αὐτοῦ,\">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>] Latin <i>delicias ejus,</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Pol.” 1303b23. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__A.2</b></Level3> without sexual reference, <b>love warmly,</b> opposed to [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" φιλέω, οὐδ᾽ ἤρα οὐδ᾽ ἐφίλει Plato Philosophus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Lysis” 222a \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]:—and in <i>passive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" ὥστε οὐ μόνον φιλοῖο ἂν ἀλλὰ καὶ ἐρῷο Xenophon Historicus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Hiero” 11.11, compare 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Brut.” 29; κινεῖ [τὸ οὗ ἕνεκα] ὡς ἐρώμενον 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 1072b3 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]. <br /><Level2><b>__A.II</b></Level2> with <i>genitive</i> <i>of things</i>, <b>love</b> or <b>desire passionately,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" τυραννίδος 7th c.BC: Archilochus Lyricus 25.3; τερπνότατον τοῦ τις ἐρᾷ τὸ τυχεῖν 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 256; μάχης ἐρῶν Aeschylus Tragicus [{4-5th c.BC}] “Septem contra Thebas” 392; μόνος θεῶν γὰρ Θάνατος οὐ δώρων ἐρᾷ [prev\\. author] “fragment” 161; ἀμηχάνων ἐρᾷς 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 90; πατρίδος ἐρᾶν 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 359; οὗ ἐπιθυμεῖ τε καὶ ἐρᾷ Plato Philosophus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Symposium” 200a \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]: and with <i>infinitive</i>, <b>desire</b> to do, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “fragment” 44.1; θανεῖν ἐρᾷ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 220; ἀποθανεῖν ἐρῶντες 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ τέχνης” 7; φαγεῖν Aristophanes Comicus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Acharnenses” 146; πληροῦσθαι Plato Philosophus [{5-6th c.BC}] “Philebus” 35a \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>].","strongNumber":"G7493","accentedUnicode":"ἐράω","shortDef":"to love passionately","mediumDef":"to love passionately","stepGloss":"to love passionately","stepTransliteration":"eraō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb"}]}